."],"variants":[{"name":"Isolda","meanings":["The name of the tragic mistress of Tristan in the Arthurian romances. There are several versions of the story. The main features are that the beautiful Isolde, an Irish princess, is betrothed to the aged King Mark of Cornwall. However, through accidentally drinking a magic potion, she and the young Cornish knight Tristan fall in love, with tragic consequences. The story has exercised a powerful hold on the European imagination. The name was relatively common in Britain in the Middle Ages, but is much rarer today."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":0,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Isolde Oerct was born in 1382, in Alnwick, Northumberland, England, her father, Francis D'Oerct, was 22 and her mother, Margaret Anna De Charlton, was 17. She married Johnannes Kynaston on 21 July 1403, in Ellesmere, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died in 1435, in England, at the age of 53."},"et":{"1382–1435":"1382–1435","1381–1403":"1381–1403","1395–1476":"1395–1476","1399–1425":"1399–1425","1360–1436":"1360–1436","1365–1399":"1365–1399","Abt 1425":"umbes 1425","1395":"1395","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1381":"1381","1436":"1436","1425":"1425","1403":"1403","1435":"1435","1399":"1399","1476":"1476","1365":"1365","21 JUL 1403":"21. juuli 1403","Alnwick, Northumberland, England":"Alnwick, Northumberland, England","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Shrewsbury Shropshire England":"Shrewsbury, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Underwood, Derby